posts.cooked: Is there any COTS options for 5v input to 12v output at 3a buck boosts, I am having trouble finding any, as most are either at too low of an amperage, or convert 12v to 5v. For context, we are trying to power a Bee Link MINI S N5095. Any suggestions are well apreciated!

posts.name: Joshua J
posts.cooked: Why is it that you need a 5V input?
Its not strictly a 5v, but we are concerned about battery voltage drops when our drive kicks in. In reality I think what we need is around 5-7v in.

posts.name: s-neff
posts.cooked:
Why do you want to start at 5v? Can you do 7-14v to 12v regulator instead?

The reason you are not finding that part is P1=P2=IV

P=(3a)(12v) = (5v)(target amps) (Target Amps) = 3*12/5 = 7.2a at 5v

Your 5v source almost certainly won’t do 7A for you.

Edit: OH, you want the minimum dropout voltage on the regulator to be 5v. That’s an expensive regulator. You will brown out other components at around 7v, no reason not to use a more common parts. If your drive is pushing you under 8v, solve your drive problems instead of hardening everything else.

posts.name: Joshua J
posts.cooked: Edit: @asid61 is definitely correct. I mixed up some numbers.

posts.name: Anand Rajamani
posts.cooked:
It’s pretty common to go under 8V transients while driving. Completely above brownout range.

Finding a 5-14V to 12V buck boost is tricky. I recommend just scrolling through Amazon until you find one. I believe there is a diagram in my Mini PC guide showing how to parallelize cheaper regulators to make a more reliable one. That’s the route I recommend, unless you want to order a bunch on Amazon and see which actually brown out under 8V before returning the rest.

I would not get a regulator rated for 8V minimum input voltage. It will likely brown out. You’re welcome to test one, however, and see if it will work for your needs.
